Against the scale of suffering that was commonplace here in the first 30 years of Communist rule, the two women were minor casualties, incidental figures in a huge tableau of repression. But they were Americans, and the punishment they endured seems to have been senseless even by the obscure standards of the time. Seraphine and Marjorie Fuller, a devoutly Christian mother and daughter living quietly by themselves in Shanghai, answered a knock on the door one day in 1959 to find agents of the feared Public Security Bureau waiting to take them to a labor camp.
